title: Channel 10 lawyers up over Bachelorette spoiler
text:
Email a friend 
CHANNEL 10 has won an injunction against The Daily Mail after it posted photographs spoiling the season finale of The Bachelorette. 
Just hours before the program was about to air, Daily Mail Australia published images of Bachelorette Sam Frost canoodling with her chosen beau (Sasha Mielczarek) in a Sydney hotel. 
The broadcaster quickly took out the injunction against Dailymail.com Australia Pty Ltd seeking it to remove the pictures and subsequent article from its website and other electronic media under its control. 
It also requested the British-owned website remove social media posts and other documents and electronic communications containing the images and content of the article. 
The injunction was filed in the Supreme Court of New South Wales this evening. 
The order states the plaintiff (Network Ten) was seeking to file a summons in court seeking relief over the publication of the images and article, as well as filing fees. 
It also says the website be banned from republishing the same pictures and content. 
News.com.au understands Dailymail.com Australia was informed about the injunction around 8pm. 
Not long after, the pictures and article were removed from its site and social media. 
But it was up long enough to do some damage with those on social media venting their frustration and disgust over the website ruining the finale. Don't watch the show (friend updates are enough) but boo to the Daily Mail for announcing who the Bachelorette chooses. — Amy Remeikis (@AmyRemeikis) October 22, 2015 I CAN'T BELIEVE DAILY MAIL FKN RUINED THE BACHELORETTE FINALE I'M PISSED — jenan deeb (@jxnann) October 22, 2015 IF YOU DONT WANT THE BACHELORETTE SPOILT DONT GO ONTO THE DAILY MAIL WEBSITE FML — Gabrielle || 21 ✨ (@Gxbriellemxry) October 22, 2015 Daughter 2 is expressing loud disdain for the #dailymail . #TheBacheloretteAu has served a worthwhile purpose. — Mark Scott (@mscott) October 22, 2015 
When asked if it intended to still seek damages against the website, a Network Ten spokesperson said: “No comment”.
